The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, May 12: The country?s industrial growth rate went up to 8 per cent during the fiscal ended March 31 from 7 per cent in 2003-04. However, the growth had slowed down to 7.2 per cent in March compared with 8.1 per cent a year ago. An 8.8 per cent growth in the manufacturing sector propelled the industrial growth rate in 2004-05. The sector had grown by 7.4 per cent in 2003-04, according to figures released by the government today. The electricity sector stagnated at 5.2 per cent against 5.1 per cent in 2003-04. The mining sector slowed down to 4.3 per cent from 5.2 per cent a year ago. The index for industrial production stood at 204.2 points last year compared with 189 in 2003-04. 

 New Delhi, May 12: The government today moved two bills in the Lok Sabha to give tax authorities more powers. The Taxation Laws (Amendment) Bill seeks to provide for ?provisional attachment of property? of persons on whom a notice is served for excise dues. The second bill proposes to prescribe mandatory filing of returns by charitable institutions. 

 Mumbai, May 12: Textile stocks rallied on bourses today after the Supreme Court paved the way for the development of mill lands. Reports of China?s revaluing the yuan also led buyers chasing these stocks as the sector is expected to benefit from it.

 New Delhi, May 12: The Lok Sabha today approved the amendments to the special economic zone (SEZ) bill, which had been incorporated in the Rajya Sabha at the insistence of the Left parties. 

 Mumbai, May 12: Sebi will simplify procedures for secondary offers of firms which are actively traded on bourses and have a track record for continuous disclosures, said chairman M. Damodaran.

 Mumbai, May 12: A Reserve Bank working group on warehouse receipts and commodity futures has recommended that banks should be permitted to offer non-standard contracts as well as derivative-based products to farmers to hedge their commodity price risk.




